<BaseLayout title="Research — Hyungwoo Song" lang="en"><section class="page-hero"><div class="wrap"><div class="eyebrow">Research direction</div><h1 class="page-title">When AI enters human life, what should become more humane?</h1><p class="lead">My Ph.D. research centers human-centered AI and accessibility, asking how technology reshapes agency, voice, learning, and care.</p></div></section><section class="section tight"><div class="wrap research-principles"><article><span>01</span><h2>Agency</h2><p>I study conditions under which AI helps people understand and keep their own judgment, rather than simply taking decisions away.</p></article><article><span>02</span><h2>Voice</h2><p>I examine what kinds of translation or adjustment are required for a voice to be heard as legitimate, and how AI changes that process.</p></article><article><span>03</span><h2>Access</h2><p>Accessibility is not only feature delivery; it is about enabling equal participation in education, information, and care.</p></article><article><span>04</span><h2>Care</h2><p>In healthcare and workplace contexts, I study how technology engages uncertainty, vulnerability, and adaptation.</p></article></div></section><section class="section"><div class="wrap grid two"><article class="card"><span class="stamp">Thread</span><h3>Accessibility and inclusive interaction</h3><p>Projects such as EmoBridge, AltAuthor, and AltCAT study accessibility across classrooms, screen readers, and cultural contexts.</p></article><article class="card"><span class="stamp">Thread</span><h3>Human-centered AI and information access</h3><p>AI shopping agents, argument search, and review experiences reveal how AI shapes interpretation and choice.</p></article><article class="card"><span class="stamp">Thread</span><h3>Healthcare and social adaptation</h3><p>MediBridge-related work asks what people cannot ask, and what support is needed in unfamiliar institutional and healthcare journeys.</p></article><article class="card"><span class="stamp">Thread</span><h3>Learning and reflection</h3><p>In classrooms, academic reading, and code comprehension, I study whether AI can scaffold thought rather than only accelerate answers.</p></article></div></section></BaseLayout>